<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Minister of State in the Office
of the President John Koech has announced that he resigned from
the Kenyan Cabinet with immediate effect, the "Daily Nation"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Koech, accompanied by his bodyguard, went to the Nakuru bureau
of "Daily Nation" yesterday and wrote an open letter to President
Daniel arap Moi, saying that he had resigned as a minister.
</P>
<P>
He stated that he would give a comprehensive statement next
Monday and stressed that "this is an open letter. I can't change
my mind. I have resigned. I am no longer (President D.A.) Moi's
minister."
</P>
<P>
The daily paper said that the resignation came barely a
fortnight after President Moi pardoned Kipkalia Kones, former
Minister of State whom Koech replaced in January this year.
</P>
<P>
The two politicians from Bomet District have been political
rivals since the election of Kones to Parliament during the last
General Election in 1992 and his appointment to the Cabinet the
same year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
