<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fredericks Clocks 9.99 Seconds in Men's Heats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Frank Fredericks of Namibia, Olympic
silver medallist last year, clocked 9.99 seconds in the men's 100
meters second round here this evening at the 6th World Athletics
Championships.
</P>
<P>
His time is the third fastest in the second round, behind Trinidad
and Tobago's Ato Boldon's 9.87 and American Maurice Greene's 9.90. Tim
Montgomery of the United States also ran 9.99 in front of world record
holder Donovan Bailey of Canada's 10.10. All these big names sailed
into the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
The track looks fast at the newly-built Olympic stadium and
Bailey's world record of 9.84 seems in danger.
</P>
<P>
Boldon, Olympic 100m and 200m bronze medallist last year, is in
splendid form. He would have beaten the record if he had not eased up
in the final strides today.
</P>
<P>
But Bailey was not that good. The Canadian finished second in both
the first and second rounds.
</P>
<P>
Boldon said after the race:"My dream is under 9.80, but certainly I
would be happy with 9.81. I want to see what everyone else is doing in
this round. In the last 10 seconds before the race started, I
concentrated on staying down, keeping my pattern because if I pop out
of the blocks my race is over. That is what I did in Atlanta."
</P>
<P>
The 100 meters final will be held on Sunday, and the world record
is most likely erased by Boldon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
