<HEADLINE> Taliban Ready to Cooperate with UN in Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia were ready to cooperate with the United Nations and
Pakistan in their efforts for restoration of peace in the war-torn
Afghanistan, a senior Taliban official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban also favored the formation of a broad-based
political commission "which should include all Afghan groups,
small and large and not just the Northern Alliance", Muhammad
Ghaus, member of the Taliban Central Shura, was quoted by the
Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ghaus, Taliban's former foreign minister, held three-hour talks
with Pakistani Additional Foreign Secretary Iftikhar Murshed who
arrived today in Kandahar, a major city in southern Afghanistan,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The Kandahar talks focused on proposals for a ceasefire,
exchange of prisoners and the establishment of a joint commission
by the warring sides to work out a political settlement, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Murshed, who has conducted his shuttle diplomacy to bring the
afghan warring factions back to the negotiating table, described
Taliban's proposal for the formation of a political commission for
the settlement of Afghan conflict as a "breakthrough."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
