<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns Israeli Security Policy on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today condemned Israel's
tough security measures against the Palestinians, saying they
would only worsen the situation.
</P>
<P>
After two suicide bombings killed 14 people and wounded 150
others in a vegetable market in Jewish West Jerusalem Wednesday,
Israel immediately imposed a closure on the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, barring tens of thousands of Palestinians from their jobs
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was worried that Israel's security measures were
counterproductive and went beyond its legitimate security
concerns, said Acting Minister of State for Information Affairs
Nasser Lawzi after a special cabinet meeting to discuss current
situation.
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan reported today that Jordanian Foreign Minister
Fayez Tarawneh has contacted Israeli and United States officials
to urge Israel not to overdo security measures in the Palestinian
self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Such Israeli security measures could only lead to more
tensions, the foreign minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lawzi also criticized the Israeli closure of the Palestinian
territories after the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's suicide bombings have been the newest terrorist
violence in the region since the peace process was stalled in
mid-March this year due to the construction of a Jewish settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The construction triggered conflicts between the Palestinian
stone-throwers and Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
During the deadlock of the Israeli-Palestinian talks, the
Israeli closures of the Palestinian self-rule area has led to an
increased unemployment and deterioration of the Palestinian
national economy.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt are the only countries in the Arab
world that achieve peace with the Jewish state while both serve as
mediators in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
