<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Linguists Call for More Efforts to Cultivate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leipzig, Germany, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Over 250 African
linguists attending the Second World Congress on African Languages
in Leipzig today called on African governments to pay more
attention to cultivate the much-neglected local languages.
</P>
<P>
According to Congress Chairman cultural Wolff, delegates from
more than 40 African nations agreed that the variety of languages
in Africa should be viewed as cultural wealth instead of obstacles
to development.
</P>
<P>
They called on national governments to help provide textbooks
and other teaching materials in as many African languages as
possible. More intensive linguistic studies were also urged to
preserve the 1,200 languages and dialects in use in Africa, most
of which lack a written form or do not have any grammar books or
dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
The congress is due to convene every three years in Africa,
Europe and North America after its launching in Swaziland in 1994.
Leipzig was chosen as the venue for the congress because the
Leipzig University has been teaching African languages since 1895.
An institute for African studies was also founded there in 1993
which now has 130 students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
