<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cracks Threaten Defences in Eastern German </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- German soldiers and other helpers
worked frantically today to repair several cracks emerged in the
sodden dikes along the flooded Oder River on the border with
Poland to prevent the flooding of thousands of homes.
</P>
<P>
It was described as a miracle for the dikes in the Oderbruch
region of eastern Germany to be able to withstand the
unprecedented high water levels for the past 15 days. The dikes
were designed only to hold floodwaters for three to four days,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
"We are standing with the back to the wall," said Michael Muth,
leader of the local crisis committee. The battle against flooding
had led to unprecedented use of materials and manpower.
Nevertheless, the danger of dike bursts was higher than ever
before, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the floodwaters remained at high levels on the
Oder or receded only a few centimetres at some locations. Real
relief would only come when the water levels drop by at least 1.5
metres, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Manfred Stolpe, state premier of the eastern German state of
Brandenburg, predicted this morning that the crisis situation
would still persist for eight to nine days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rescue workers had begun to construct a
3.2-kilometre-long emergency dike behind the primary one in
southern Oderbruch region. This would contain floodwaters in an
uninhabited area in the event of a major dike collapse, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
German Defence Minister Volker Ruehe told the German newspaper
Bild am Sonntag that German troops, who had been leading the
battle against the flood over the past two weeks, would remain in
the region even after the crisis. They were expected to help
rebuild the damaged infrastructure and clean the environment, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
