<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor Names 15-man Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's President Charles Taylor
has reportedly named a 15-member cabinet for his new government
inaugurated today, the News Agency of Nigeria quoted Liberian
newspapers as having reported.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 named are Tome Woewiyou for labor, Roosevelt
Johnson for transport and Francois Massaquoi for youth and
sports.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of the three is seen by most Liberians as a sign
of Taylor's promise to forge unity and encourage reconciliation
in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Woeweiyou was Taylor's spokesman at the outbreak of
hostilities in 1989 and later broke ranks with him, while Johnson
and Massaquoi belonged to different warring factions and
political groups.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the cabinet also consists of at least
six persons who had served in previous governments from Tolbert's
regime to the Ruth Perry-led Council of State, the provisional
ruling body before Taylor's inauguration today.
</P>
<P>
These include Monie Captan for foreign affairs, Joe Mulbah for
information, Edward Sackor for internal affairs, Woewiyou Ernest
Eastman as minister of state and General Philip Kamah for
national security.
</P>
<P>
Other ministers are Peter Jaliah for justice, Bangali Fofana
for commerce, Roland Massaquoi for agriculture, Jenkins Dunbar
for land, mines and energy, John Richardson for public works, D.
Chea for defense and Joe Tate as commissioner for the bureau of
immigration.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, whose rebel fight against the late President Samuel
Doe triggered off the bitter civil war seven years ago, was sworn
in as the 21st president of the country in the capital Monrovia
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Taylor's inauguration came after his landslide victory in the
July 19 election, marking the end to the country's seven-year
bloody civil war that killed nearly 200,000 people, displaced
about a million others and destroyed the national economy.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural address, President Taylor urged Liberians to
help him set new changes and goals for the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
Taylor promised to follow the order of law and respect human
rights, while assuring Liberians that there will be no witch
hunting.
</P>
<P>
He also called his former opponents to join him in rebuilding
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that Taylor's administration is facing the
daunting task of reconstruction of the country which Taylor
helped destroy in the past seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
