<HEADLINE> Crackdown on Animal Smuggling Urged in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Nigerian environmental
protection official has called for the stricter enforcement of
the country's law against rare animal smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Adegoke Adegoroye, director-general of the Federal
Environmental Protection Agency expressed his concern over the
spate of illegal smuggling wildlife species, in an interview with
the News Agency of Nigeria recently.
</P>
<P>
He condemned those Nigerians that are involved in the hunting,
capture and trade of rare animals and stressed the need to
enlighten the public on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Adegoroye called on the diplomatic society to support and
cooperate with the Nigerian government in preserving wildlife
species.
</P>
<P>
The official's call came after two highly endangered drill
monkeys smuggled from Nigeria to the Philippines in 1995 were
returned to the country earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Drills are large, short-tailed rain forest monkeys that live
only in Nigeria, Cameroun and Equatorial Guinea. Its total
population is estimated to be between 2,000 or 3,000, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
