<HEADLINE> Russia to Help Turkmenistan in Air Force Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia has agreed to continue
helping Turkmenistan develop its air defenses and air force, the
Interfax news agency quoted the Russian air defense press service
as reporting on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was made during a visit to Ashkhabad, the Turkmen
capital, by Russian air defense commander Viktor Prudnikov several
days ago.
</P>
<P>
The assistance will comprise two stages: the first stage (from
the rest of 1997 to 1998) would involve training personnel,
restoring radar control along Turkmenistan's borders, creating a
missile shield for the Central Asian country's capital Ashkhabad
and making Turkmen aircraft combat ready.
</P>
<P>
During the second stage, in 1999-2000, Russia would help to
complete the building of a stable radar monitoring system for
Turkmenistan and control centers for the country's air defense
forces.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Moscow also considers supplying
Ashkhabad city air defenses with an S-300 missile system.
</P>
<P>
During Prudnikov's visit to Ashkhabad the two sides also
discussed control of the air space over the Caspian Sea,
interaction between Russian and Turkmen air defense forces and
training and retraining Turkmen personnel in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
