<HEADLINE> Bagach Snatches First Gold Medal in World Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Aleksandr Bagach of Ukraine came from
behind to win the first gold medal of the 6th World Athletics
Championships here Saturday night with a mighty toss of 21.47 meters.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion John Godina of the United States was beaten into
second place, three centimeters shy of the winner. Oliver-Sven Buder
of Germany wound up third at 21.24.
</P>
<P>
Godina opened strongly with a 21.24 toss and increased the lead to
21.39 in the next try. But Bagach, who landed a pair of 20.55 and
20.60, turned the table on the third round, unleashing his winner.
</P>
<P>
Buder improved his personal best with the medal winning distance,
beating C.J. Hunter of the United States, whose best mark this year
was 21.34.
</P>
<P>
World record holder and Olympic champion Randy Barnes of the United
States slumped in the qualifying round, finishing a distance 14th.
</P>
<P>
Bagach said after his triumph:"I thought Godina and Barnes would
be the most serious opponents. I am so sorry for Barnes. Today he
was under the unfluence of bad luck."
</P>
<P>
The winner revealed:"I have undergone doping control this year and
this will make six, but this doesn't matter."
</P>
<P>
A disappointed Godina said:"I messed up. There was no way I should
have lost today. It is just one of those things I will have to deal
with."
</P>
<P>
Buder was just happy about the result. "It is an unforgettable day
for me. Before the championships it looked that only the fourth berth
in the final would be open to me, but Barnes' elimination changed
everything." 
</P>
</TEXT>
