<HEADLINE> Daniel Garcia Caps Men's 20km Walk World Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Daniel Garcia of Mexico moved in front
in the final stage to win the men's 20-kilometer walk gold medal here
Saturday night at the 6th World Athletics Championships.
</P>
<P>
His winning time was one hour, 21 minutes 43 seconds ahead of
Mikhail Shchennikov of Russia's 1:21.53 and Mikhail Khmeinitsky of
Belarus's 1:22.01.
</P>
<P>
With seven of the first eight from the previous championships
returned to battle for the world crown, the race was tough throughout.
</P>
<P>
Ilya Markov and Shchennikov led the pace at the start and opened a
sizable lead 24 minutes after the race. But Ilya was sent out 30
minutes later while he was still in front.
</P>
<P>
Garcia, this year's World Cup silver medallist, seized the chance
to take the pace, followed by Shchennikov and Khmeinitsky.
</P>
<P>
Garcia, who was disqualified after entering the stadium in third
position in the 1993 world championships, and suffered the same fate
250 meters from the finish at the previous meet, maintained the
leading position confidently.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion and the year's leader Jefferson Perez of Ecuador
finished poorly in 14th.
</P>
<P>
Garcia said after the win:"I started to race very slowly and that
was my tactic for the victory. This win was my great aim after my
disqualifications in the previous two championships. For me, this
medal is worth three golds. I saw that Jefferson was not strong after
the 14 kilometers, and I was feeling strong myself."
</P>
<P>
Shchennikov was not satisfied with the result. "Frankly speaking I
don't understand why I had two warnings. The most critical moment came
when I heard the steps of Garcia behind me. I had to slow down my
pace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
