<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish State Minister Isin Celebi has said that
Turkey has started a campaign to boost annual exports to 50
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2002 with the creation of new
free zones and reduced taxes, local newspaper Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Celebi made the remarks Friday at a meeting of the Turkish
Exporters Assembly in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Celebi said that the newly-established coalition government
would raise the number of free trade and industrial zones to boost
exports from an estimated 23 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Turkey currently has eight free zones, including those in the
ports in Mersin, Antalya, Trabzon, Istanbul and Mardin and the
total trade volume of the zones were 3.6 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is planning to open an industrial zone in Thrace to
specialize in textiles and garment production and exports and a
trade zone in the Black Sea port city of Samsun, which will have
insurance, packing and storage facilities.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Italy will provide Lebanon with three soft loans
totalling 60 million U.S. dollars under an agreement signed Friday
by Italian Ambassador to Lebanon Calo Carlia and Nabil Jisr,
Lebanese president of the Council for Development and
Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The English Newspaper Daily Star reported Saturday morning that
the loans with a 0.5 percent interest rate are payable over 35
years. The money will be spent on water and electricity networks.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 7 million dollars will be used in health
care in eastern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Italy, the biggest trade partner of Lebanon, had a trade
volume of 950 million dollars with Lebanon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian-Moroccan Chamber of Commerce has decided
to establish a joint holding company with a capital of 300 million
U.S. dollars to develop trade between the two countries, according
to the latest issue of Egyptian economic weekly Middle East News.
</P>
<P>
As of next September, executive measures will be taken to
establish a free trade zone between the two countries to fix the
list of commodities to be exempted from customs duties of both
countries, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
