<HEADLINE> Mkapa Stresses Importance of Self-reliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
today called on members of Parliament to educate the people on
the need to be self-reliant to bring their development as less
donor assistance was now forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the special parliamentary committee session of the
ruling Revolutionary Party (CCM) in Dodoma, central Tanzania,
Mkapa, who doubles as CCM Chairman, said there is need to review
the 1995 CCM election manifesto which made several promises which
can be fulfilled with people's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said there is also need to invite private investors and
non-governmental organizations to help in implementation of some
promises made which can be implemented by them.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa admitted that promises in the CCM election manifesto
were not made to seek praise to CCM, but it was to the problems
that need to be removed, for example, an investor can construct a
bridge over the Kigammboni creek and operate it commercially.
</P>
<P>
Privatization, he said, has shown that it can make things move
as shown by production with the Tanzania Breweries and Tanzania
Cigarette companies which now bring twice as much revenue to the
government after being privatized.
</P>
<P>
Although it was anticipated that government revenue collection
would increase by 19.5 percent from now up to the year 2000,
foreign aid would go down by two thirds, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Foreign aid would go down from 186.5 billion Tanzania
shillings (about 310.8 million US Dollars) in 1996/97 to 61
billion T. Shs. (about 101.6 million US Dollars) in 1999/2000, he
said, adding that up to June this year only 30 percent of this
had been given.
</P>
<P>
The CCM chairman said many projects which were being
implemented with donor assistance were stalled as the government
was supposed to contribute counterpart funds, which were not
available.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that projects which can be implemented with
assistance from the people, should be implemented that way as the
government had too may things to do and was cash strapped.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, primary schools country-wide require
148,000 latrines but there were only 43,000. "Can't the people
build these lavatories on self-help basis?" Mkapa asked.
</P>
<P>
He said the MPs and Himself will be judged by what they had
fulfilled to the people during the next election in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The CCM chairman said waiting for the government to do what
can be done by the people would very much relay development to
the people, noting that people must cultivate the spirit of self
sufficiency in themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
