<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bagach Wins First Gold, Boldon Shocks World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Aleksandr Bagach of Ukraine claimed
the first gold medal, but Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tobago robbed the
highlight of the first day competition at the 6th World Athletics
Championships by clocking a sizzling time in the men's 100 meters
second round here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bagach came from behind to beat defending champion and the year's
world leader John Godina of the United States in the men's shot put
final with a 21.47-meter winning toss.
</P>
<P>
The day's other gold medal was won by Daniel Garciaa of Mexico when
the World Cup silver medallist shaked off his bad luck to win the
men's 20-kilometer walk in one hour, 21 minutes 43 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Boldon, Olympic bronze medallist in both the 100m and 200m who is
keeping the year's best times this season, threatened Donovan Bailey's
world record of 9.84 seconds in the 100m second round, blazing down
the fast track with an unbelievable time of 9.87.
</P>
<P>
His time is only 0.03 seconds shy of the world record, and if he
had not eased up in the final strides, he would have broken the globe
mark in the heats!
</P>
<P>
Boldon said:"My dream is under 9.80 seconds. I wanted to see what
everyone else is doing in this round. Now I feel I am ready to beat
the world record."
</P>
<P>
Mauice Green of the United States, the fastest American sprinter
with a 9.90 personal best, wound up second behind Boldon in the group
with a brilliant time 9.90.
</P>
<P>
Bailey looked pale in the first two rounds, finishing second in
10.10. His world record may not survive this time under Boldon's feet
in the final tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
In the men's shot put final, Godina placed second at 21.43m, ahead
of Oliver-Sven Buder of Germany's 21.24.
</P>
<P>
Godina opened strongly with a 21.24 toss and increased his lead to
21.39 in the next try. But Bagach, who landed a pair of 20.55 and
20.60, turned the table on the third round, unleashing his mighty
winner. World record holder and Olympic champion Randy Barnes of the
United States slumped in the qualifying round, finishing a distance
14th.
</P>
<P>
Bagach said after his triumph:"I thought Godina and Barnes would be
the most serious opponents. I am so sorry for Barnes."
</P>
<P>
Godina was upset, saying:"I messed up. There was no way I should
have lost today. It is one of those things I will have deal with."
</P>
<P>
The men's 20km walk saw seven of the first eight from the previous
championships return to battle the world title. Ilya Markov and
Mikhail Shchennikov, both from Russia, led the pace in the first 24
minutes. But Ilya was sent out 30 minutes later while he was still in
front.
</P>
<P>
Garcia, who was disqualified after entering the stadium in third
position in the 1993 World Championships, and suffered the same fate
250 meters from the finish at the previous meet, ended his bad luck by
winning his first world title.
</P>
<P>
Shchennikov and Mikhail Khmeinitsky of Belarus took the silver and
bronze respectively. Olympic champion and the year's best time setter
Jefferson Perez of Ecuador wrapped up 14th.
</P>
<P>
Garcia said after the win:"I started to race very slowly and that
was my tactic for the victory. This win was great aim after my
disqualifications in the previous two championships. For me, this
medal is worth three."
</P>
<P>
In the women's 100m second round, Marion Jones of the United States
romped home in 10.96 seconds. The fastest runner was Zhanna
Pintussevich of Ukraine who clocked 10.90.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Merlene Ottey of Jamaica was still very powerful in
the race, hitting the 11 second to lead her group.
</P>
<P>
The day also witnessed the disppointed failures of some other big
names.
</P>
<P>
In the women's triple jump qualifying, world record holder Inessa
Kravets of Ukraine pulled out of the competition in front of the sand
pit. Anna Biryukova of Russia, the 1993 world champion and the first
woman over 15 meters, injured her knee on the first round.
</P>
<P>
Sunday will feature three finals - the men's and women's 100m
finals and men's hammer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
