<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Clear Land-mines in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 2 (xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Army needs
more than 13.6 million U.S. Dollars to clear hundreds of
thousands of land mines scattered along the country's borders in
five years, an army officer said today.
</P>
<P>
Director of engineering corps colonel Sibangumuzi Khumala said
the money would be used for buying mine clearing, logistics and
camping equipment to replace the current outdated and dilapidated
machinery.
</P>
<P>
He was briefing general James Jamerson, U.S. deputy commander
in chief for Europe and Africa who is on a three-day visit to
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Currently the army has two mine clearing teams, but we have
proposed to set up six teams once we get the necessary funding to
enable us to effectively deal with the problem," Khumala said,
adding the army would carry out the exercise far much cheaper
than a private contractor.
</P>
<P>
He said the European Union last year funded Zimbabwe to clear
a stretch of land along the north-western border, a big sum which
the army could use to clear the whole country of land mines.
</P>
<P>
General Jamerson is expected to make a U.S. defense force
commitment to assisting its Zimbabwean counterparts in ridding
the country of land mines planted by the Rhodesian army at the
height of the liberation war to control armed incursions by
guerillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
