<HEADLINE> Doohan Wins Brazilian Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Michael Doohan
strengthened his grip on the 1997 world title when he won the
Brazilian 500cc Grand Prix on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It was Doohan's ninth win in 10 races this season -- and his
seventh straight -- as the three-time world champion continued to
dominate the season on his Repsol Honda.
</P>
<P>
Doohan, starting from pole for the seventh straight race, was
once again unstoppable over the 4.933km Jacarepagua circuit
despite his traditional slow start. He was clocked 45 minutes
05.793 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The Australian was in the lead by halfway through the first of
the 24 laps and stayed there, despite a determined challenge from
Japan's Tadayuki Okada, who finished second on his Honda --
7/10ths of a second behind.
</P>
<P>
Luca Cadalora of Italy was third on his Yamaha.
</P>
<P>
Doohan now has 245 points from a possible 250 with five
championship races remaining. Okada is second on 129 points with
Nobuatsu Aoki of Japan third on 126.
</P>
<P>
The Repsol Honda team have now won all 10 of this season's
races so far and Doohan is closing in on Italian Giacomo
Agostini's record of 11 wins in a season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
