<HEADLINE> Johnson Almost out of Men's 400m Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Michael Johnson of
the United States almost failed to qualify for the semifinals of the
men's 400 meters when he ran a slow time of 45.39 seconds in the
second round at the 6th World Athletics Championships here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic champion finished fourth in his group and placed 15th
among the 16 qualifiers. He led the field off the final curve, but
eased up on the home straight. Ibrahima Wade of Senegal kicked hard
and nipped him at the line.
</P>
<P>
Johnson said after the race:"I was sure I had a firm grip on my
position. I just didn't see him, it surprised me that he was suddenly
beside me."
</P>
<P>
The fastest qualifier was Jerome Young of the United States in
44.87 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Johnson injured his leg in the 150-meter race against Donovan
Bailey of Canada on June 1. His 54 winning streak for the 400m over
eight years snapped last month in Europe. The Olympic hero looked just
like a shadow of his best days.  
</P>
