<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Bans Air Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Belgium suspended all aerobatics
flights to be held on Belgian military airports until the
investigation result of the July 26 crash at an air show comes
out, local television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The air show at a civil airport in Moorsele near Courtrai,
scheduled on August 23 and 24, is also cancelled.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Defense Minister Jean-Pol Poncelet has ordered an
assistant to investigate into the organization of aerobatics
flights in the country after a Jordanian aerobatics plane crashed
during performance in the seaside resort of Ostend.
</P>
<P>
Nine people were killed and 55 injured when the German-made
Falcon biplane, piloted by the leader of the Jordanian royal air
display team, lost control while doing a looping stunt and crashed
into the crowd around a Red Cross tent near the runway.
</P>
<P>
Eleven injured victims, most of whom burnt by the kerosene
sprayed by the plane when it hit the ground and burst into flames,
are still receiving treatment in hospital.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that the plane was flying overhead the
spectators while doing the stunt, which was forbidden by air show
rules.
</P>
<P>
Primary probes showed that several other planes also flew
overhead the spectators on the day. The report has caused concerns
of the military authorities.
</P>
<P>
Air shows are popular summer events in Belgium, drawing many
visitors each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
