<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Police Step Up Triad Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong police are stepping
up their surveillance on triads to prevent Macao's wave of
organized crime violence spilling over into Hong Kong, the Sunday
Morning Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Secretary for Security of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Peter Lai Hing-ling as
saying that a ban had been placed on suspected gang members
entering from Macao.
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper said the HKSAR government was
concerned about escalating crimes in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"Suspected people who are not Hong Kong residents will be
denied entry. We cannot ban those who are Hong Kong residents, but
police will strengthen monitoring their activities," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
He warned Hong Kong residents planning to go to Macao for
holidays or work to be especially careful.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he released some figures showing a continuing drop in
Hong Kong's overall crime rate.
</P>
<P>
According to him, overall crime dropped 16.4 percent to 34,421
cases in the first six months of this year from the same period of
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
