<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President: Greek Cypriots Remain Positive for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said here today Cyprus is determined to show a positive
attitude toward international efforts to achieve a solution to the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a commemoration service here for the
20th anniversary of the death of first president of the Republic
of Cyprus, Archbishop Makarios III.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that Cyprus is at a crucial crossroads, but
despite the difficulties that lie ahead, the Greek Cypriot side
will show the same positive attitude at the second round of
direct talks, scheduled to take place in Switzerland on August
11-16, as in the first round of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash held their
first round of direct talks under the U.N. auspices near New
York on July 9-12 and agreed to continue negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Clerides and Denktash held two meetings here under
the U.N. auspices to reach an agreement on the humanitarian
issue of missing persons during the event of 1974 Turkish
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side has expressed the hope that Denktash
will attend the second round of talks in August. Denktash has
threatened not to take part in the direct talks after the
European Union reaffirmed last month a decision to begin EU
accession talks with Cyprus early next year.
</P>
<P>
Clerides reiterated that "we know that the solution to the
Cyprus problem will be a compromise, but we will not accept a
compromise that threatens the independence and territorial
integrity of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of the failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
