<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya's Reactions to IMF Loan Suspension  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Wang Jinyu)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Different reactions have been
made by Kenyan government and opposition leaders and leaders of
religious orgnizations following the decision by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to halt an aid package to the
country.
</P>
<P>
On July 31, the IMF decided to suspend a three-year Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) amounting to 215 million
U.S. Dollars because of the alleged failure by the Kenyan
government "to show its commitment to fighting corruption".
</P>
<P>
In response to the IMF decision, Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi said on Auguest 1 that the Kenyan government " would not
succumb to threats, intimidations or ultimatums as it had a duty
to protect all Kenyans."
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia Mudavadi
announced a chop in the 1997/98 financial year expenditure
accompanied by revenue measures to address the shortfall caused
by the IMF decision.
</P>
<P>
"Sunday Times" today carried an editorial, criticizing the IMF
for applying double standards to African countries regarding
political and economic liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The paper run by the ruling Kenya African National Union
pointed out that Kenya had done almost all that was required by
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, "everytime the government carries out
particular reforms, more demands are quick to surface," adding
that " When new demands are being made, those that have been met
by the government are deliberately forgotten."
</P>
<P>
Certain African countries are yet to implement multi-partism,
it noted, they continue to receive support from the West without
endless conditionalities.
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi Kiptanui, the National Deputy Chairman of the Kenya
Muslims Supreme Council, noted that the IMF decision was aimed at
causing chaos in the East African country.
</P>
<P>
Kenyans were fed up with external pressures and would not
succumb to foreigners on how to run their own affairs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Head of Kenya Catholic Church Archbishop Ndingi Nzeki also
criticized the IMF for cutting the loan, arguing that since the
reform process in the country had been put into gear, the IMF had
no business "interfering" with it.
</P>
<P>
And Musikari Kombo, branch Chairman of opposition FORD-Kenya
in Bungoma District, has attributed Kenya's economic instability
to more than 30 years of over-reliance on external funding.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Deputy Leader of the opposition National Convention
Executive Council, James Orengo, Saturday asked Kenyan
Attorney-General Amos Wako to take appropriate actions to
prosecute the individuals involved in the massive fraudulent
diversion of transit sugar into the local market.
</P>
<P>
The IMF was reportedly concerned by the sudden removing last
month of Samuel Chebii from the post of Commissioner of Customs
and Excise, who was investigating the import of sugar by
companies with links to some politicians.
</P>
<P>
Chebii had been "undoubtedly removed from his post as he had
stringently fought" against the dumping of imported transit sugar
into the local market, the IMF has said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the IMF was also angered by repeated
scandals in kenya's energy, customs and agricultrure sectors that
led to huge losses.
</P>
<P>
Mwai Kibaki, Chairman of the opposition Democratic Party of
Kenya, pointed out that the government had known that the IMF
could withhold aid if corruption was not brought under control
and the government should have taken appropriate actions to deal
with the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
