<HEADLINE> Report: Saddam's Son Uday to Be Treated in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's
eldest son Uday, is to be operated on here to remove from his
spinal cord a bullet shot at him in an ambush last year, Middle
East Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The English weekly, in its latest edition, cited unnamed
sources as saying that Egyptian authorities have given "the green
light to the hospitalization of Uday Saddam Hussein in Cairo on
humanitarian grounds."
</P>
<P>
"A team of surgeons specializing in bones and neurology will be
chosen to operate on Uday in a Cairo hospital," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats in Amman said that foreign surgeons would be
called in to assist in the "very delicate operation."
</P>
<P>
The sources said that contacts had been made with the United
Nations to authorize Uday to fly to the Egyptian capital from
Baghdad, the capital of Iraq, which has been under an
international air embargo since Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Uday, 33, left hospital on June 9, six months after gunmen
sprayed his car with bullets in the center of Baghdad on December
12. Iraqi officials said he made a "full recovery" although he
appeared on crutches.
</P>
<P>
German surgeons operated on Uday's leg in April with reported
success but did not want to perform the delicate spinal cord
operation in an Iraqi hospital because of the poor conditions and
lack of medical equipment, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi authorities have announced no arrests in the
assassination bid, while Uday has pointed a finger at Iran, which
fought an eight-year war against Iraq from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
