<HEADLINE> S. Leone Prepares for Tightening ECOWAS Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 3 (Xinhua)- About 28,000 metric tons of
diesel and generating oil for electricity were brought into
Freetown early today from Nigeria as west african states are
to tighten their sanctions against Sierra leone.
</P>
<P>
Wo Chunchi, captain of the Chinese vessel, said two other
vessels are expected in Freetown shortly with petrol and
kerosene.
</P>
<P>
The consignment was loaded off the dock by Chinese
and local workers.
</P>
<P>
The generating oil arrived in time to save the city from being
plunged into darkness as oil reserves for electricity power had
almost dwindled.
</P>
<P>
"This is just a stroke of luck in the best of timing," said
one dock worker.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the National Petroleum Company (NPC) said the
oil stock will last for four to five months and it is enough to
give a 24 hours non-stop light in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The oil consignment follows the arrival of crucial rice stock
of some 6,000 metric tonnes last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said the military government is acting
urgently to "collect all vital stocks of petroleum and other
commodities in anticipation of a tightening of sanctions by the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) after the
collapsed talks in Abidjan last week.
</P>
<P>
Delegation of the military government to the failed Abidjan
talks are expected to return here on Monday after visits to
Burkina Faso and Togo to explore avenues for the talks to be
reconvened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
