<HEADLINE> Afghan Fighting Rages as Pakistan Resumes Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between the Afghan
Islamic Taliban militia and their rivals continued to rage north
of Kabul as Pakistan resumed its peace efforts in the war-torn
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces edged their frontlines forward as the
militia regained control of the town of Hossein Kot, about 20 km
north of Kabul, where the Taliban and their rivals have been
fighting over the past week, according to reports monitored here
today.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's gains represent the first change in more than a
week of deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The forces loyal to Ahmad Masood captured Hossein Kot late July
in a major surprise offensive which has brought them to within
rocket range of Kabul. However, since then both sides have failed
to gain any significant ground north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
While fighting continued to rage north of Kabul, Iftikhar
Murshed, Pakistani Additional Foreign Secretary on Afghanistan,
expressed here today the hope for holding an intra-Afghan dialogue
under the UN auspices soon.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying very hard for holding an intra-Afghan dialogue
for peace in Afghanistan and one is always optimistic," said
Murshed today when talking to reporters about his latest visit to
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Murshed, who on Saturday visited Kandahar, the Taliban's
stronghold in southern Afghanistan, said that he expected to fly
to Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the anti-Taliban northern
alliance, on Monday for talks with the alliance leaders.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 km north of
Kabul, last month, Murshed rallied a positive response from the
alliance leaders including Masood and Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Murshed had secured the Taliban's support for the
formation of a political commission from the Taliban's former
foreign minister Muhammad Ghaus.
</P>
<P>
Murshed described Ghaus' offer as a "breakthrough and
step-forward" in diplomatic efforts for peace in the war-battered
country.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban northern alliance had forwarded the idea of
setting up a political commission for the formation of a
broad-based government in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
However, Ghaus, member of the Taliban Central Shura, has
stressed that the political commission should include not just the
northern alliance but other Afghan groups as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
