<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communist Party Fosters Capable Officials (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: China has scored great progress in its reform
and opening-up efforts since the convocation of the 14th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) in October,
1992. Beginning today, Xinhua will mark this fall's opening of the
15th CPC National Congress with a special column outlining the
monumental success the third generation leadership of the CPC
Central Committee headed by Jiang Zemin has achieved in accordance
with Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The past five years have witnessed
the introduction of a series of CPC Central Committee decisions
designed to raise the quality of leading officials and select
outstanding young officials.
</P>
<P>
Since the holding of the 14th CPC National Congress, Party
committees at various levels and relevant organization departments
have given priority to enhancing the competence of officials in
line with Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Statistics covering the 1992-1996 period show that more than
500,000 officials above county level received training, and over
1,000 officials at the ministerial level participated in study
courses sponsored by the Party School of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Party committees and organization departments at various levels
have accelerated efforts to select officials in line with
requirements set by CPC Central Committee General Secretary Jiang
Zemin, and have in turn strengthened supervision in order to
ensure a clean government.
</P>
<P>
In-depth studies of model Communist Party members, including
Kong Fansen who was dedicated to his assignment in the Tibet
Autonomous Region, have provided leading officials with the
political and ideological awareness needed to carry forward the
fine tradition's of the Party.
</P>
<P>
Local Party organizations, including those in Shanghai and the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, have successfully sponsored
diverse activities which have helped improve the ideological and
political quality of officials.
</P>
<P>
Replacing older officials with younger ones has gradually
rationalized the age structure of leading officials. A large
number of highly competent educated people with high level
profession ability have been promoted to leadership positions at
various levels.
</P>
<P>
The number of provincial, prefectural and county leading
officials holding college degrees has jumped by 14.7, 12.6 and
10.2 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more people proficient at business management or
with good scientific and technological knowledge have been
promoted to leading positions at various. The new appointees have
demonstrated their initiative by helping to invigorate the Chinese
nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communist Party Fosters Capable Officials (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, close attention has been paid to ensuring that new
officials inherit and carry forward the fine traditions and work
styles of the Party. This has helped build a contingent of capable
party officials readily adapted to new conditions associated with
a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Party organizations at various levels have educated
officials, leading officials in particular, in the need to
improve ties between officialdom and the general public, and in
wholeheartedly serving the people.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials in Liaoyang, Northeast China's Liaoning
Province, have forged closer ties with local residents by
exhibiting special concern for the needy.
</P>
<P>
Work experience in grassroots units has been taken as an an
important criterion for promoting an official.
</P>
<P>
Officials indulging in ostentatious life styles or those
unwilling to work in grass roots units, as well as those incapable
of identifying themselves with the masses or those who are unable
to solve problems stand to no chance for promotion.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, Party efforts to strengthen leading bodies and
official ranks have followed the principle of "promoting those who
are acknowledged by the general public as adhering to the Party's
line of the reform and opening-up, and who have recorded
merits in performing their duties."
</P>
<P>
Effective measures introduced since the last national congress
in 1992 have strengthened efforts to build the Party's leading
bodies and official ranks. Related efforts have included improving
the quality and ideology of leading officials at various levels,
as well as promoting and training outstanding young officials.
</P>
<P>
The large number of highly proficient model officials emerging
over the past few years have contributed greatly to educating
people and improving the cohesiveness of the Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
