<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Earnings Rise 13 Percent in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export earnings for
the fiscal 1996-97 stood at 4.418 billion U.S. dollars, an
increase of 13 percent from the figures in the previous year,
according to statistics released by the Bangladesh Export
Promotion Bureau (EPB).
</P>
<P>
There was a mixed trend in export earnings from different items
during the fiscal year ended June 30, as receipts from some major
commodities came down abnormally while the earnings from some
items sharply picked up.
</P>
<P>
According to the EPB, earnings from garments, the country's
major foreign exchange earning sector, showed a downward trend.
Earnings from this sector were 2.7 percent below the target of the
fiscal year but 14.84 percent higher than that of the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Total export earnings from garments in 1996-97 fiscal year
reached 2.237 billion dollars against a target of 2.3 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, earnings from leather exports in the fiscal year
were about 29 percent below the target and 7.66 percent down from
the earnings in 1995-96 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from shipment of frozen food in the fiscal year showed
an abnormally downward trend, earning only 320.73 million dollars,
about 23.64 percent below the target.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from jute goods during 1996-97 also were 20.5
percent below the target and 3.36 percent down from the export
receipts during the previous fiscal year, said the EPB.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, export receipts from knitwear products in
1996-97 were 49.67 percent ahead of the target and 27.57 percent
down from the receipts during 1995-96 fiscal.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exported knitwear items worth 763.3 million dollars
in 1996-97 while the target was fixed at 510 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The EPB said that earnings from shipment of agriculture
products also rose up from 21 million dollars in 1995-95 to 28.65
million in 1996-97.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
