<HEADLINE> S. Africa Trys to Beef up Justice System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Minister of
Justice Dullah Omar will ask the cabinet to appoint one thousand
new court officials to boost the ailing justice system, local
daily Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Omar as saying that he would urge the
cabinet to approve a 65.2-million U.S. dollar scheme to improve
the national court system with three-to-four hundred extra
prosecutors, and one-to-two hundred extra magistrates, as well as
72 new regional courts.
</P>
<P>
Omar said he was also seeking to improve the pay package for
prosecutors, who were leaving because "they are not treated as
professionals".
</P>
<P>
According to Omar, South Africa's financial budget for the
court system, which is at just one percent of the total budget,
was "probably the lowest in the world".
</P>
<P>
Last week, Omar said that the cabinet would study a draft
legislation to put bail beyond the reach of suspects accused of
murder, rape, car hijacking and other serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
Local observers noticed that the South African government are
trying to amend its existing judicial systems in a bid to curb
increasing vicious crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
