<HEADLINE> Nigeria Spends Billion Dollars on Liberian Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian head of state Sani Abacha
said Saturday that his country has spent no less
than three billion U.S. dollars on the Liberian peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while attending the inauguration ceremony
of Liberian's newly-elected President Charles Taylor in Monrovia,
which marks the culmination of the Liberian peace process mainly brokered
by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was the among the first west African countries to send
its soldiers to sub-regional peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG
in August 1990, eight months after the Liberian civil war broke
out.
</P>
<P>
Through the seven years of peace-keeping, Liberia contributed
the largest force as well as most of the material and financial
support to ECOMOG, the strength of which increased from the
beginning 3,000 men to 12,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As General Abacha put it, "The road to peace in Liberia has
not been easy". It has been won "in blood, sweat and the
commitment of vast resources of the states of the sub-region",
he added.
</P>
<P>
The peace-keeping mission in Liberia is unique. The
peace-keepers had to fight directly with the armed factions for
their very survival and presence.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, there have been peace-keepers who were killed,
captured or injured, though their exact number is not known as
this moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
