<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Popular Musician Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Fela Anikulapo-Kuti, the
originator of Afrobeat, and the popular and controversial Nigerian
musician died Saturday at the age of 59.
</P>
<P>
His death was announced by his family in Lagos. But the
announcement did not say where he died.
</P>
<P>
What is known to the media is that he had been ill for a long
time and was hospitalized in a Lagos hospital. But some reports
said he may have returned to his home town in Abeokuta, Ongo
State, in southwest Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Fela was born on October 15, 1938. He formed his first band
in 1959 in London, where he was attending the Trinity College of
Music, Oxford from 1959 to 1962.
</P>
<P>
Fela leaves behind him over 40 music albums. Known as King of
Afrobeat, he is the most popular musician in Nigeria and his
influence went beyond his own country.
</P>
<P>
Most of his works are believed to have political undertones
which led to his strained relations with the authority.
</P>
<P>
His private life is most controversial. He was reportedly
married to 27 wives and is known to be using Indian hemp for
which his home was raided by the police for two times, the second
time just several months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
