<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf States Shelve Single Currency Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Arab states have shelved a
plan to unify their currencies as part of a long-standing drive to
create a common market, a senior Omani official said in an
interview published here today.
</P>
<P>
Hamud bin Hashem, executive president of the Omani Central
Bank, said the issue had been discussed at several meetings of
finance ministry and central bank officials of the six-member
Gulf Cooperation Council(GCC).
</P>
<P>
"All of them affirmed that exchange rates in the GCC are
stable and do not constitute any restrictions on the movement of
trade, investment and capital among them," he told the Arab daily
Al-Ittihad.
</P>
<P>
"They agreed to continue with the current arrangements for
exchange rates and postpone discussions of the common currency
peg," he said.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states had planned to create a single currency called
the Gulf dinar for their planned common market, which will also
include a customs union. But they abandoned such a project and
opted instead for unification of their exchange rates, a plan that
has been under negotiations for years.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said the currency project was held up by reservations
by some members on proposals to unlink their currencies from the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Except for Kuwait, whose dinar is tied to a basket of major
currencies, the national currencies of the GCC states are
effectively linked to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed on encouraging expansion in using national
currencies in member states and boosting coordination in monetary
policies." Hashem said.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Kuwait, the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Bahrain
and Qatar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Victor Moves Away, Leaving One Dead in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon Victor, the worst to
hit Hong Kong in 14 years, moved away from the region early
this morning after killing one person and injuring at least 55
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The first typhoon of the season this year, Victor, packing
winds of between 110 kph and 120 kph, was centered over Hong Kong
last night, and was moving further into Guangdong Province, some
150 kilometers north-northwest of Hong Kong, at 03:30 this
morning, weather forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
The No. 9 Typhoon Signal was raised at 04:50 on Saturday
afternoon, the first time since 1983. It was lowered to No 8
shortly before midnight after Victor was weakening into a "severe
tropical storm."
</P>
<P>
The No. 8 signal was lowered at 03:30 this morning and replaced
by the No, 3 Strong Wind Signal.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, a 44-year-old British man who
drowned off Stanley was among the three people who were pulled
from the rough seas. Another person plucked from the water was in
satisfactory condition in hospital, while a third person was not
injured.
</P>
<P>
At least 55 people were reported injured but most were treated
in hospital for minor injuries and released.
</P>
<P>
With the same hurricane-force wind, Typhoon Ellen swept across
Hong Kong in 1983, killing 10 people and injuring over 300.
</P>
<P>
This time, Victor also caused transport chaos, bringing buses,
ferries, planes and taxis to a virtual standstill. On Saturday,
over 322 flights were cancelled or delayed.
</P>
<P>
Victor formed in the South China Sea on Thursday and appeared
to be headed for Hainan Island before changing course and bearing
down on Hong Kong. It was Upgraded to a No. 3 storm at 10:00 on
Friday morning and then to a No. 8 on Saturday at noon.
</P>
<P>
Weather watchers said the storm gained quickly as it approached
Hong Kong. For just the third time in history the center of a
typhoon crossed directly over the urban area with heavy rains. Up
to 200 millimeters of rain fell in Hong Kong by midnight between
Saturday and today.
</P>
<P>
Typhoon Victor passed between Hong Kong Island and Lantau
Island at about 08:00 on Saturday evening, and then crossed the
Tsing Ma Bridge before making landfall near Tsuen Wan.
</P>
<P>
At the Hong Kong International Airport, more than 320 flights
were affected. Among them, 49 incoming flights were cancelled, 84
delayed and 30 diverted. For departure, 68 flights were cancelled
and 91 delayed.
</P>
<P>
The Local authorities suspended all bus, ferry and tram
services by 19:30 on Saturday, while the open sections of the Mass
Transit Railway were closed half an hour earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Kowloon-Guangzhou Railway suspended services at the same
time, while the Light Rail Transit services were suspended from
20:30 on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, two east-bound lanes of Wong Chuk Hang Road were
closed near the Grantham Hospital due to dangerous scaffolding,
while Cooper Road, Happy Valley, and Island Road were closed due
to a tree fall as were Shaouson Hill Road, Aberdeen and the Shek
O-bound Tai Tam Road.
</P>
<P>
There were also reports of flooding, landslip, fallen trees,
dangerous signboards or concrete plaster and dangerous
scaffoldings and canopies.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region has opened 39 shelters in various districts.
Early this morning, 312 people were reportedly using the
facilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
