Asian Nations (ASEAN) has expressed its hope for a free and fair
election in Cambodia, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's hope was sounded as the ASEAN mediating team, which
comprises foreign ministers of Indonesia, Thailand and the
Philippines, met with Cambodia's second Prime Minister Hun Sen in
Phnom Penh on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Prince Norodom Ranariddh's participation in the election next
year is very important for Cambodia to demonstrate to the
international community that the election would be free and fair,
Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn said after returning to
Bangkok Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, who led the ASEAN
mediating team, also said in Phnom Penh on Saturday that the
election would be meaningless without free participation of all
political parties.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen reportedly had expressed his desire to hold a free and
fair election as scheduled for May next year, with the
participation of all political parties and individuals, including
supporters of Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC Party.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed welcome to international observers and a
coordinating role by the United Nations in the election.  
