<HEADLINE> Jordanian Prime Minister Ends Visit to UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Salam al Majali today ended his visit to the United Arab Emirates
with a call on Israel to give Palestinians legal rights.
</P>
<P>
According to UAE's Wam news agency, Majali, during his second
visit here in a little more than a month, said Israel should give
Palestinians legal rights so as to realize peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We are regretful over the latest matters in the Middle East
peace process. We do not think Israel could get peace without
giving Palestinians legal rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, the Jordanian premier held discussions with
senior UAE officials on the latest developments in the Middle East
region in the wake of a double suicide bombings in a major
vegetable and fruit market in Jerusalem killing 15 people and
wounding over 150 others.
</P>
<P>
Majali attacked measures taken by Israel after the bloody
bombings, saying they "violated Palestinians' rights."
</P>
<P>
"Israel should condemn itself, not another side. I do not
think the Palestinian Authority is an abettor of violence," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Israel has imposed closure of the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
arrested more than 70 Palestinians, blaming the Palestinian
Authority for the violence and threatened to re-enter Palestinian
self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
During the talks today, UAE's vice premier said UAE is also
seriously concerned over the deteriorated Middle East peace
process and it called Israel to change its settlement policies to
resume peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We called for the resumption of peace negotiations which have
reached an impasse because of Israel's settlement policies in Arab
Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
A just, comprehensive peace should be obtained on the basis of
giving Palestinians legal rights, allowing them to establish
their own state on their lands with Jerusalem as the capital, and
implementing the land-for-peace principle, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also called the United States and Russia, the two key
sponsors of the Middle East peace process to force Israel to
change its hardline policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
