<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Confirmed as Iran's New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Most Iranians were relieved to
watch the transfer of the highest executive power from outgoing
President Hashemi Rafsanjani to his moderate successor, the
incoming President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony today attended by ministers, high-ranking
government officials and foreign diplomats, Khatami was conferred
with the confirmation from Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
the top politico-religious figure towering above the country.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, 54, was minister of culture and Islamic guidance for
about 10 years. He resigned in 1992 and became cultural adviser to
Rafsanjani and head of National Library of Iran.
</P>
<P>
In his acceptance speech the moderate cleric offered olive
branch to the world while vowing to carry on the legacy of the
founder of the Islamic Revolution, late spiritual leader Ayatollah
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
"At the international level, we seek to establish peace and
security ... peace and security for all nations and that is why we
oppose expansionism of great powers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation, read by Rafsanjani on Khamenei's behalf,
requested the new president to adhere to the roads and principles
of the Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
"It goes without saying that my decree would, like the votes of
the people, remain valid as long as the president would ... stand
against the tyrannical and oppressive enemies of Iran," read the
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
In his speech today, Khamenei urged Khatami to devise plans to
fight widespread poverty across Iran. Two thirds of the country's
60 million population is believed to be living under the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts should be spent that poverty, injustice and
discrimination would be eliminated in Iran," Khamenei said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's predecessor, President Rafsanjani, sounded relieved
in stepping down after two four-year terms in power, whose liberal
policies paying off in breathing life to the country's war-torn
economy.
</P>
<P>
"The person who is giving up the responsibility is feeling
relaxed and unburdened, and the person who is taking over is
feeling the responsibility," Rafsanjani said in farewell speech.
</P>
<P>
On Monday Khatami is expected to attend Iran's Parliament and
be sworn in as Iran's fifth president since the Islamic
Revolution of 1979. Iran's system of rule before the revolution
was a monarchical rule dating back to 500 B.C.
</P>
<P>
Entering the presidential race with a liberal platform, Khatami
gained over 20 million votes, the highest votes ever secured by
any Iranian president, in May presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
His arch competitor, conservative Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar
Nateq Nouri, obtained only 7 million votes.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Khatami will have an uphill battle
ahead with a Majlis (parliament) dominated by the conservatives,
which has called on Khatami to discuss his choice of ministers
with them.
</P>
<P>
So far Khatami has refused to give in to pressures from the
270-seat Parliament to reveal the names of his ministers.
</P>
<P>
Local press here today said the new president will introduce
his cabinet to the Parliament on August 9 and 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kunming Striving to Increase Urban Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Kunming, the capital city of the
southwestern Yunnan Province, is working hard to increase the
capacity of water supply in its urban area so as to cope with its
serious water shortage problem.
</P>
<P>
The city government plans to invest more than three billion
yuan (361 million US dollars) for the short and long-term plans to
bring in additional 300 million cubic meters of water annually.
</P>
<P>
At present, the annual water supply for the city with an urban
population of some two million residents was only 195 million
cubic meters, with a daily deficiency of about 200,000 cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
According to the Overall Municipal Construction Program, the
annual water supply to the main urban area will be 330 million
cubic meters by the year 2000, 400 million cubic meters by 2010
and 476 million cubic meters by 2020.
</P>
<P>
So the city party committee and government took emergency
measures and introduced a water-diversion project in its adjacent
area. An investment of 200 million yuan (24 billion US dollars)
will be made in two years for providing some 800,000 of its urban
residents with 50 million cubic meters of water, and the project
is expected to be completed in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in an effort to put an end to water supply shortage,
the Kunming city government has resolved to channel water from
Zhangjiu River, a tributary of the Jinsha River in Southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year project, which is scheduled to be launched in
1999, will require an investment of 2.9 billion yuan (349 million
US dollars) in building a complete reservoir network with pumping
stations, water diversion channels, and waterworks. It is reported
that the Ministry of Construction has listed it among the 23 major
city water supply projects, which are subjected to the State
Planning Commission for approval.
</P>
<P>
This program will help ease the burden of Dianchi Lake, the
leading source of water supply for urban residents, and to
alleviate the sewage pollution for the local environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Seeks to Boost Oil Output Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi oil official
announced that Iraq can now export nearly 2.5 million barrels of
crude oil each day.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper "Al-Qadissiya" today quoted Taha Mahmoud
Moussa, senior under-secretary of the Oil Ministry as saying the
country will be capable of export 3 million barrels per day after
some simple technical requisites are fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is now ready to resume exporting oil since U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan has approved its distribution plan for food and
medicine under the "food-for-oil" deal with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
It has marketed all the amount of oil provided for by the
renewed formula with the U.N. for another six months, which
reaches 120 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeking - within our future plan - to increase our
crude-oil production capacity to 6 million barrels per day, and
to bring our oil reserves to some 320 billion barrels instead of
112 billion barrels at present," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Iraq possesses oil fields that have not
been exploited yet.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Iraq is continuing efforts to increase its
oil-refining capacity, develop its giant oil fields and discover
new ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
