<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Revolutionary Relics Urged at National Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A national conference on
protection of historical relics with revolutionary content opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng, in his congratulatory message to the
conference, said that China is a country with a glorious
revolutionary history. The abundance of revolutionary relics gives
an expression to the great, noble spirit of the Chinese nation and
the members of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
In the new period, he added, the work in this sector should be
carried out under the guidance of Marxism, Leninism, Mao Zedong
Thought and Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics and adhere to the orientation of serving
socialism and the masses of people.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech, State Councillor Li Tieying said that with
the kind attention the CPC and the central government, China has
built some 300 revolutionary museums and memorial halls and 7,000
cemeteries of revolutionary martyrs and listed 8,000 sites of
historical relics under key protection.
</P>
<P>
Relics of revolution occupies a special status in promoting
socialist ethics and ideological progress. It is essential to
fully utilize these relics, add still more such relics and
increase their protection, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for increased efforts and doing a still better job in
collecting, sorting out and studying historical relics, and in
conducting general surveys and working out plans for protection.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he urged Party committees and governments at all
levels to increase input in relics protection.
</P>
<P>
Both Li Yuanchao, vice-minister of culture, and Zhang Wenbin,
drector of the State Bureau of Cultural Relics, addressed the
meeting, which is attended by representatives of the central
government departments, provincial officials in charge of the work
concerning relics protection and curators of leading revolutionary
museums and memorial halls, as well as noted experts and
scholars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Takes on Seles in WTA Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- World number one Martina
Hingis and former number one Monica Seles will have their third
final-meeting at the 450,000 U.S. dollar WTA Toshiba Classic after
both scored straight-set triumphs in semifinals Saturday at San
Diego, California.
</P>
<P>
Hingis breezed Mary Pierce 6-0, 6-2 in just under 50 minutes
while the second seeded American Seles beat third seed Amanda
Coetzer of South Africa 6-3, 6-4, in the other semi-final.
</P>
<P>
Hingis will seek her ninth WTA Tour title of the season. As the
youngest Wimbledon winner this century, she also has won the
Australian Open, the Sydney International, Pan Pacific Open, Open
Gaz de France, the Lipton and Family Circle Cup.
</P>
<P>
Hingis has bettered her match record to 53-1 this year after
this semifinal. Seles has a 26-8 record but has lost her four
finals this year, two of them to Hingis.
</P>
<P>
The top prize will be 79,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
