<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Women Urged to Fight for Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean cabinet minister
Saturday called on the Zimbabwean women to continue the fight for
their rights to realise their dream of being equal with men.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual conference of the Women's Action Group
in Harare, Thenjiwe Lesabe, Minister of National Affairs,
employment creation and cooperatives, discouraged women from
being bribed to vote men into power.
</P>
<P>
"If they buy you mealie-meal, clothes or anything, take but do
not vote for them," she said. "We need more women at power
points. Your vote is your constitutional right, use it."
</P>
<P>
She urged the women to take advantage of the 25 percent quota
system introduced by the government to elect capable women for
positions in the public services.
</P>
<P>
"We want women to be both politically and economically
empowered," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Lesabe announced that Zimbabwe had submitted its first report
on the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination Against Women, which it acceded to in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
