<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Stresses Security Cooperation in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Information Minister
Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah has underlined the need to activate
multilateral organizations to safeguard collective security in the
Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The minister voiced his proposition in an interview with the
Kuwait television last night on the seventh anniversary of Iraqi
invasion of the small but rich Gulf country.
</P>
<P>
He said that regional safety and security need to be guaranteed
through the six-member Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), the
enlarged Damascus Declaration and other defense treaties with a
number of states that took part in the international alliance to
liberate Kuwait in the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is a member of the GCC which also groups Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirate, Oman, Bahrain and Qatar. In March 1991, soon
after the Gulf War ended, the six nations signed with Syria and
Egypt the Damascus Declaration to beef up security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait also signed with the United States and other western
countries a number of security agreements to strengthen its
position in collective security.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, the Kuwaiti minister again warned the
people against "existing Iraqi regime's threats to Kuwait,"
stressing the 1990-91 Iraqi aggression against Kuwait was
also directed against the GCC.
</P>
<P>
He called on Kuwait and other GCC countries to devise options
to defend themselves against any similar aggression in the
future.
</P>
<P>
While touching on the suffering of the Iraqi people under the
stricture of U.N. imposed sanctions, the minister blamed the Iraqi
regime for the plight of its people. However, he cautioned, any
attempt to overthrow the regime of Saddam Hussein would lead to
bloodshed in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On normalizing relations with countries siding with Iraq in the
Gulf War, Sheikh Saud said the issue was carefully studied by the
concerned authorities with Kuwait's interests as the focal point.
</P>
<P>
"The restoration of relations is not an emotional issue but
rather a matter of state interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he maintained that "a clear position should be made by
the leadership of these states."
</P>
<P>
Concerning Kuwaiti-Palestinian relations, Sheikh Saud stressed
that "our dispute with the Palestinian leadership is due to its
position during the Iraqi aggression but we support the legitimate
rights of the Palestinian people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
