<HEADLINE> Environmental Degradation Causes Loss to India Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- India is losing at least 10
percent of its national income due to environmental degradation,
said a latest study by the Tata Energy Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The study report, which focuses on the state of India's natural
resources between 1947-1997, is slated to be released by Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral on August 6, a government official
said today.
</P>
<P>
On the 50th anniversary of India's Independence later this
month, the availability of fresh water has declined by two-thirds
over the past 50 years, the area covered by soil degradation has
increased by almost 80 million hectares, spelling doom for
agricultural productivity.
</P>
<P>
The area covered by forests has increased by four percent but
half of it is covered by low crown-density or degraded forests.
Livestock grazing in the forests is three times the desirable
level and cultivated land per capita has halved, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The over-exploitation of groundwater is an acute problem in the
agriculturally important districts, where production is expected
to be severely hit, as costs of extracting water from a falling
groundwater table go up. The annual agricultural output is also
being hit by rapid soil degradation which has already consumed a
whopping 57 percent of the country's area.
</P>
<P>
Apart from soil erosion, waterlogging, salinization and
nutrient depletion are responsible for a loss of up to 26 percent
of the annual agricultural output today, the study said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
