<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Former Tribe Chief Faces Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Lucas Mangope, former
"President" of Black-homeland Bophuthatswana in apartheid South
Africa, will appear in court Monday on 18 charges of theft
involving about 200,000 U.S.Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mangope, allegedly deposited the public money belonging to the
Bahurutshe-Boo-Manyane in the "Republic of Bophuthatswana", which was
established by the white minority regime during the apartheid
era.
</P>
<P>
Mangope has been chief of the Bahurutshe-Boo-Manyane tribe
since 1959.
</P>
<P>
The alleged theft took place between 1979 and January 1994.
The money was intended for the tribe authorities after a chrome
mining company damaged a farm whose surface rights were owned by
the tribe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
