<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Police Put on Full Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan police have been put on
full alert since last Wednesday when thugs threw a grenade at
civilians near Kibuye in the capital Kampala, the local daily
''The New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a public rally held last evening in Fort Portal,
southwestern Uganda, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said,
''Those engaged in urban terrorism in kampala will face the full
wrath of the country's security agencies."
</P>
<P>
He assured the people that the government troops will soon
wipe out the Ugandan rebels of the Allied Democratic Force (ADF).
</P>
<P>
Local mass media held that consecutive grenade attacks at
Kibuye, Natete and Nakulabye in the capital were committed by
ADF.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of State for Defence Amama Mbabazi said
yesterday that so far the grenade attack issue has been a police
matter, but if the situation escalates, the Ugandan army is ready
to involve in.
</P>
<P>
Army Commander Mugisha Muntu yesterday met senior army
officers during which they discussed the grenade attacks, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Two people have so far been arrested in connection with the
attacks in which at least 10 people have died and 72 others
injured since Wednesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
