<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Capital Leads Nation in Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- India's capital New Delhi leads
the national table on crime growth rate, the Hindustan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A classified document of the National Crime Records Bureau,
tabulating 1996 crime figures, puts the number of cognizable crime
cases in New Delhi during the year at 59,871.
</P>
<P>
In specific crimes, Delhi's graph is marked with an appreciable
increase over the last four years with a net hike of 25.6 percent
from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 88.7 percent of the total crimes in the capital were
under the category of "kidnapping and abduction" of children. In
net terms, crimes of this nature increased by 64.35 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Cases of rape and molestation also increased by 44.5 percent
and 33.5 percent respectively in the city in 1996 as compared to
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
A total number of cognizable crimes in the country registered
an increase of 3.2 percent in 1996 as compared to the previous
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
