<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telephone Ownership Reaches 55 Percent in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The telephone ownership in
Shanghai municipality, China's commercial and financial center,
reached 55 percent by the end of June, taking a leading position
among the Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Latest breakdowns from the Shanghai Telephone Bureau show that
telephone subscribers in the municipality rose by 336,000 in the
first six months of this year, bringing the total number of users
to 3.37 million, of which the number of telephones in residents'
houses amounted 2.5 million, accounting to 55 percent of the total
households in the city.
</P>
<P>
It took more than a century for Shanghai to extend the number
of telephone subscribers from single one in 1882 to one million in
1993. The figure doubled subsequently in three years between 1993
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicated that every Shanghai resident in the
first-half year dialed 450 local calls and 15 long-distance
calls. Quite a few households even installed two telephones for
their fax machines or computers.
</P>
<P>
The increase in telephone ownership has also helped change the
mix of postal services. The telegraph businesses, for instance,
went down 30 percent annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Shanghai is expected to add 1.2 to 1.45 million
telephones in the next three years, a net increase of 800 to 900
users per day, according to estimations of the relevant municipal
departments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
