<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flash Flood Hits Southern Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Flash Flood, caused by incessant
rainfall in the last three days and onrush of water from the
hills, hit Cox's Bazar district in southern Bangladesh, leaving at
least 150,000 people marooned in flood water.
</P>
<P>
Road links between Cox's Bazar and the country's second largest
city of Chittagong were cut off early Saturday as the highway went
under four feet water at Nalbila area, according to reports
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, surging sea-tide caused by the monsoon depression
over the Bay inundated the low-lying areas of the district. Sea
water entered through the branches and inundated the coastal
areas.
</P>
<P>
At least one thousand acres of seed beds and 20,000 acres of
standing crop are badly affected by the floods while the rivers
Matamuhuri, Bagkhali and Eadgong are flowing one feet above the
danger level.
</P>
<P>
The floods have destroyed 450 houses and damaged another 1,500,
said the local authorities, adding that they have sanctioned 20
tons of rice and 25,000 taka (about 575 U.S. dollars) in cash for
distribution among the flood affected people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
