<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Strike Runs Into Third Week in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 2 (Xinhua) -- As the soccer strike in
Argentina entered into the third week today, the final solution to
the problem was still not in sight.
</P>
<P>
Sparked by the disarray between six players and their club in
late July, the nationwide strike was called upon by labor union
Argentine Soccer Players Guild on July 22.
</P>
<P>
The union made the decision in response to a court ruling on
July 15 that the players had to remain in the Deportivo Espanol
Club even if their contracts expired on June 30.
</P>
<P>
The judge said the players are the property of the club now 3.8
million U.S. dollars in debt, because its creditors had decided to
prevent the club from buying or selling players.
</P>
<P>
But the players, backed by the union and the Argentine Football
Association, held that their contracts should be respected and
that they were entitled to sign contracts with any club.
</P>
<P>
On July 31, the Labor Ministry declared the strike illegal but
soccer players nationwide vowed that they would not return to the
field before the six players won their freedom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amenities Attract Financiers to Bonded Zones in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Bonded zones will continue to be
a favourite target for foreign investment for a considerably long
period, today's Beijing based China Daily quoted Zhao Yundong,
chairman of China Association of Development Zones.
</P>
<P>
Contractual foreign investment in the first half of the year on
rise in China's 15 bonded zones, while it declined 49 per cent
nationwide from a year ago, according to Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Co-operation (Moftec) sources.
</P>
<P>
Many recently approved foreign-funded projects are in bonded
areas, Moftec spokesman Hu Zhaoqing said.
</P>
<P>
Bonded zones, aside from its duty-free advantage, Zhao noted,
have more preferential policies concerning foreign investment in
China.
</P>
<P>
They are especially attractive to enterprises in
export-oriented processing, he added.
</P>
<P>
The duty-free advantage become more prominent after the removal
of the tariff-exemption on imported capital goods for enterprises
established after April 1, 1996, commented another trade expert
who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
Another major advantage of the bonded zones is that the trade
and investment climate there are similar to those of free ports
and international practices, the expert added.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign investors favoured bonded zones because they
are in coastal areas where the economy is comparably developed and
the consumption ability is relatively high.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 bonded zones, five are in the economic and
technology development zones, seven are in the special economic
zones.
</P>
<P>
Besides the geographical advantages, highly developed
expressways, airports and sea ports contribute to the prosperity
of the 15 bonded zones.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly improving infrastructure also draws foreign
investors, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Waigaoqiao Bonded Zone, established in June 1990, is
the oldest and biggest bonded zone in China. Other renowned ones
include Shenzhen Futian, Shenzhen Yantian and Zhuhai bonded zones.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate the number of foreign-funded projects and
foreign investment hit record highs last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, more than 7,000 foreign-funded
enterprises had been set up in China's bonded zones, involving 8.2
billion US dollars of foreign investment. The foreign trade volume
of the bond zones totalled 6.3 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
