<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President: Albania to Apply New Foreign Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani
said here today that his government will apply new foreign
policies to get the much-needed international support for
rebuilding the country.
</P>
<P>
Mejdani made the remarks at a joint session also attended by
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano, Speaker of the People's
Assembly Skender Gjinushi and the country's other top leaders.
</P>
<P>
Albania must establish mutually beneficial relations with other
countries through negotiations, said the president.
</P>
<P>
The criteria for measuring the country's diplomatic
achievements are the foreign trade volume, and investment and
other practical gains from other countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Albania will implement genuine opening-up policies and build
partnerships with its neighboring countries, friendly countries,
European countries and the United States, Mejdani said.
</P>
<P>
Nano, who led a high-level delegation to Italy to seek support
for Albania's revival, briefed participants of today's meeting
about the international conference held in Rome on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The international community pledged in Rome to help Albania
rebuild itself, but warned that Albania's new government must
restore public order and adopt sound economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the failure of so-called pyramid investment
schemes triggered months of anarchy in Albania, which led to the
fall of the Democratic Party government and the resignation of
president Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
A Socialist-led coalition government was elected in June.
</P>
<P>
Mejdani noted that the new government, now facing difficulties
left over by history and the recent chaos, had no option but look
forward and unite all forces to rebuild the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
