<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Government Against Lowering Minimum Working Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican government has
partially vetoed a law project calling for reducing the minimum
working age from 15 to 12, labor authorities said today.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Farid Ayales said the project could deprive
children between 12 to 15 of chances for education and interrupt
the natural development process needed for these youngsters.
</P>
<P>
The project, approved last week by a legislative commission, is
violating the spirit of the government policies tending to bar
children under age 15 from the labor market, Ayales said.
</P>
<P>
If enacted and the issue of work permits to adolescents
authorized, he warned, "these children will be peons all their
life, without opportunities to prepare themselves."
</P>
<P>
"To encourage infantile work is to condemn our youth to
ignorance and to expand the gap between the rich and the poor," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Mario Viquez, executive president of the National Children's
Patronage, said Costa Rica had an agreement with the International
Labor Organization to bar children under 15 from working.
</P>
<P>
Latest Statistics and Census General Direction figures show
60,000 Costa Rican children aged five to 17 are working in the
sectors of commerce, agriculture, livestock activities and
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
