<HEADLINE> Japan-Based OISCA to Establish Agro-Forests in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Industrial,
Spiritual and Cultural Advancement - International
(OISCA-International), a Japan-based non-governmental
organization, plans to establish agro-forests in Pakokku district,
Myanmar's Magway division.
</P>
<P>
According to today's official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar, the OISCA will plant trees in the district's Hsin creek
watershed forest areas and the Pakhangyi region of Yezagyo
township.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the group initiated a project for growing trees in
Myanmar's dry zone and in some delta regions covered by a mangrove
forest conservation project.
</P>
<P>
The group has also set up an agro-forestry training school in
the Pakhangyi region, providing extensive training in a bid to
nurture a new generation of qualified Myanmar farmers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two New Zealand companies have been carrying out
pilot projects on tree plantations in Kalaw and Heho areas of the
country's Shan state since early last year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in forest resources with different types of
forests covering about 51 percent of the country's land area.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Myanmar has been planting 37,260
hectares of forest annually since the 1992-93 fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
