<BODY>
<HEADLINE> JV Trade Firms to open in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- China's experiment of allowing
foreign companies to deal with imports and exports will soon
expand to Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Three operate in Shanghai, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
As part of its intensified efforts to enter the World Trade
Organization, China decided to let foreigners deal with foreign
trade in Shanghai's Pudong New Area and the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone last September.
</P>
<P>
It has approved three joint venture foreign trade companies on
a trial basis in Pudong involving four foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
China, which used to bar foreign companies from dealing imports
and exports on its turf, has promised to allow manufacturers to
undertake imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai and Shenzhen have been selected as the sites for the
vital reform.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-US OCT International Trading Co Ltd, one of the two
companies to open in Shenzhen, will be among the first four joint
venture trading houses approved by the State Council, said Liu
Guangqi, deputy director-general of Shenzhen Trade Development
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The other is pending approval from the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Co-operation (Moftec).
</P>
<P>
In both cases, the Shenzhen party owns a 51 per cent stake with
the remaining 49 per cent to be shared by the foreign partners,
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-US OCT International Trading Co Ltd is to be a joint
venture between Shenzhen OCT Petroleum Trading Group Corporation
and US-based Dow Trading PRC Inc.
</P>
<P>
With a planned registered capital of 100 million yuan ($12
million), the proposed company will deal with petroleum, chemical
industrial products, mechanical and electrical products, textiles
and garments.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen OTC Petroleum Trading Corp, a State trading
enterprise group with accumulative gross assets of 3.3 billion
yuan ($397.60 million) and net assets of 1.4 billion yuan ($168.70
million US dollars), has business relationships with about 40
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
US Dow Trading PRC Inc, a subsidiary of Dow Chemical Co.,
handles production and sales of raw materials, plastics and
special products.
</P>
<P>
The other pilot trading company under approval will be a joint
venture owned by the China Cereals, Oils and Foodstuffs Import and
Export Corp's Shenzhen branch and the Japan-based Nichimen Co Ltd.
</P>
<P>
With a proposed registered capital of more than 50 million yuan
($6.02 million), the pilot project will cover a wide range of
businesses including food, machinery and electronics, chemicals
and industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Liu said several other co-operative projects in Shenzhen are
applying for approval.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
