<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Brings Pollution under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, the southernmost province
of China, has taken a series of measures to reduce industrial
waste, including contaminated water, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The province spent 27 million yuan (3.3 million US dollars) in
1996 to reduce industrial pollution. Some 26 projects have been
completed.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 64.4 percent of the waste water is properly
treated, and 94.4 percent less gas is emitted into the air. Solid
waste production has been cut by 43.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-five small paper mills and projects with severe
pollution in food and beverage, power, chemical and mining sectors
were ordered to close last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 5,630 ha of land were covered with trees and
grass. The number of nature reserves totalled 73, covering 2.7
million ha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
