<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloning Still Far From Sports, Says Specialist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 2 (Xinhua) -- It is still early to say
whether there will be cloning of sportsmen, according to Henrique
de Rose, president of the Sports Medicine International Federation
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian De Rose said in an interview during the Federated
Sports Congress being held in the city of Guadalajara, the capital
of the western Mexican state of Jalisco, that a long time has to
pass for world sports to face in the next century the arrival of
identical sportsmen produced by cloning.
</P>
<P>
He added that in the future genetic engineering will be used,
but that it is difficult to know today what influence it will have
on sports, and that its application still is a matter of ethics.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of cloning, he said eleven clones of a famous
sportsman could be physically identical, but they would not have
the same capacity to act nor would give the same results of the
copied original.
</P>
<P>
He spoke of the three big challenges faced by world sports in
the third millennium. The sophistication of the Olympic games
reduces the possibility of participating in any of them as a
sportsman.
</P>
<P>
Another big problem is the commercialization of sports, which
pressures sportsmen to give better results.
</P>
<P>
The third problem is the athlete's health, the search of high
yield and the excess of marketing, which produces injuries.
</P>
<P>
He said that sportsmen use doping to achieve great results,
without consideration to health. Such situation makes
international federations search for a solution. So it is
recommended that during sports activities there should be a
specialist in sports medicine.
</P>
<P>
However, the president of the International Federation of
Sports Medicine said that in the future sports will be safer for
sportsmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
