<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Improves Shanghai's Bank Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has established itself
as the country's pre-eminent money market by using computers for
interbank loans, foreign exchange and interbank bond transactions,
"China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the first half-year, the network, called the China
Foreign Exchange Trading System, processed more than 294
billion yuan (35 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of interbank borrowing and lending averaged 2.4
billion yuan (290 million US dollars) a day, a 29 percent
year-on-year growth, according to six-month statistics provided by
the center.
</P>
<P>
The primary interbank market is reserved for dealers such as
head offices of State banks, urban credit co-operative banks and
regional financing centers. It surged 59 percent from the previous
period to 129 billion yuan (15.5 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The balance was generated by the secondary market of bank
branches, non-banking financial centers and six overseas banks
authorized to deal in Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
foreign banks were active in the money market, especially in
short-term lending.
</P>
<P>
As for foreign currency transactions, 31.8 billion US dollars
in foreign currency was traded in 124 trading days, averaging 257
million US dollars a day. That represents an eight percent
year-on-year growth.
</P>
<P>
The turnover included 29.3 billion US dollars, 16.2 billion HK
dollars and 49.7 billion Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
As the supply of foreign exchange continues to exceed demand,
the Chinese yuan surged steadily against the US and HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
The yuan rose against the US dollar to 8.2907 on June 28, from
8.2984 on December 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the yen was less stable. It plunged the first four
months, until finding support at 6.5267 per 100 yuan. Then the yen
moved upwards and hit a 7.429 high on June 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
