<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Strike Deprives Argentines of Entertainment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Argentines were deprived for
another weekend of their traditional soccer matches because of the
sixth strike of the last 66 years since the creation of
professional soccer in this country.
</P>
<P>
The labor union "Argentine Soccer Players Guild" (FAA) started
July 22 a strike of indefinite duration after the conflict that
the "Deportivo Espanol" Club had with six players, whom the club
will not let go.
</P>
<P>
The conflict started when a court decided July 15 that the six
players must continue attached to that club, even if their
contracts ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
The judge alleged that the players are the property of the
"Deportivo Espanol" club because it has a debt of 3.8 million
dollars, and because since May of 1986 it called to a meeting of
creditors, which prevents it from buying or selling players.
</P>
<P>
However, the six players claimed their contracts be respected
and also their right to freely contract with any club.
</P>
<P>
Their situation won the support of the FAA, which groups
professional soccer players in the country, and the sympathy of
the Argentine Football Association (AFA), which are mediating to
have the matches continue.
</P>
<P>
The AFA unsuccessfully requested the strike to be ended to
avoid interrupting the National Closing Tournament to be made with
the matches of August 17. The AFA proposal includes the commitment
to interrupt the 97-98 Opening Tournament if the six players are
not free to act as they desire.
</P>
<P>
Although the Labor Ministry decreed July 26 obligatory
conciliation, and on July 31 it declared the strike illegal, the
soccer players maintained their position of not resuming
activities if the six players are not declared free to contract
with any other club, defying in this way any possible economic
sanctions and the loss of the AFA juridical personality.
</P>
<P>
There have been five important strikes, apart from the present
one, during the 66 years of the professional soccer in Argentina,
caused at the beginning for the claim to the right to form a
union, later by a minimum salary, and then for the respect to the
players right to contract with any club.
</P>
<P>
Up to this moment Argentines have had two soccer-less weekends.
</P>
<P>
If the importance soccer has in the life of the Argentines is
taken into account, this strike has monopolized the attention of
all the society, to such a degree that President Carlos Menem has
received the soccer players representatives, who expressed him
their desire to end the strike.
</P>
<P>
The only way out now is the new AFA proposal of paying 3
million dollars to the "Deportivo Espanol" club creditors, then
this club releases the six players, the strike ends, and the
closing of the tournament continues.
</P>
<P>
It will be necessary until Monday to go to the judge who made
the last decision, when he returns from his winter vacation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, negotiations between AFA, FAA, and Labor Ministry
representatives continue to find a prompt solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970803.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela to Propose Iberoamerican Business Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela will propose a plan for
cooperation among small and medium-sized enterprises in the
Iberoamerican community, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The proposal will be first submitted to a regional meeting of
the coordinators of foreign ministries scheduled for Saturday
through Tuesday, said the official, Lourdes Molino.
</P>
<P>
If approved, it will be the first on the economic agenda of the
7th Iberoamerican Summit on November 8-9 in the Isla Margarita,
said Molino, a coordinator of the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is the result of consultations between the
Foreign Ministry, the Industry and Commerce Ministry and the
private sector of Venezuela, the official said.
</P>
<P>
It will be undertaken by the Interamerican Development Bank,
the Latin American Economic System, the Bolivar Program and the
International Cooperation Agency of Spain.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American Organization for Small and Medium-sized
Enterprises, and the Latin American and Caribbean Confederation of
Small and Medium-sized Enterprises will also join.
</P>
<P>
At the six previous Iberoamerican summits, nine cooperation
programs, especially on education, were approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
