<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Posts to Meet Savings Target With Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- China's postal savings sector
will strive to fulfil its annual growth target by speeding up the
Green Card projects, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
It plans to increase savings by 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion US
dollars) this year, but savings rose just 16.7 billion yuan (2
billion US dollars) in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown was attributed to the overheated stock market and
the issue of huge amounts of treasury bonds, the paper quoted Wang
Yunpeng, deputy director of the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications' Directorate-General of Posts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the postal savings sector would not adjust its annual
goal, adding "we must make more efforts to reach the target."
</P>
<P>
One way will be accelerating the Green Card project, which aims
to link the country's post offices so customers can deposit or
withdraw money at any branch.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,547 post offices in 50 cities will be linked through
computers by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, 10,000 post offices in all cities
above the county level will be linked.
</P>
<P>
Investment is expected to reach four billion yuan (481.9
million US dollars). About 1.75 billion yuan (210.8 million US
dollars) had been invested by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
China started the postal savings business in 1919, but the
business was suspended from 1950 to 1986. It expanded quickly in
the past decade and the postal savings system is facing big
changes.
</P>
<P>
Wang went on to say that the ministry, the central bank and
related departments were studying detailed reform plans that are
expected to be fixed in the second half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
